===Etymology===
{{ja-kanjitab|なぎさ|yomi=k}}

From {{inh|ja|ojp|sort=なぎさ|-}}.<ref name="KDJ">{{R:Kokugo Dai Jiten}}</ref>  Found in the ''{{w|Man'yōshú}}'', completed some time after 759 CE.<ref name="MYS">{{RQ:Manyoshu|15|3706}}, text [http://jti.lib.virginia.edu/japanese/manyoshu/Man15Yo.html#3706 here]</ref>

Possibly a compound of {{compound|lang=ja|sort=なぎさ|凪ぎ|tr1=nagi|t1=calming, dying down|pos1=the {{m|ja|連用形|tr=ren'yōkei||continuative or stem form}} of verb {{m|ja|凪ぐ|tr=nagu||to calm down, to die down|pos=as of waves or wind}}, cognate with {{m|ja|和やか|tr=nagoyaka||calm, quiet}}|磯|tr2=sa|t2=rocky shore, pebble beach}}, where ''sa'' is an ancient alternative for ''so'', the abbreviated combining reading of modern {{m|ja|磯|tr=iso}}, cognate with {{m|ja|石|tr=ishi||rock, stone}}.

The ''nagi'' element might instead derive from classical verb {{m|ja|投ぐ|tr=nagu||to beat, strike, hit; to throw, fling, cast}}; however, this classical verb evolved into modern form {{m|ja|投げる|tr=nageru}}, as the classical conjugation pattern was {{m|ja|下二段|tr=shimo nidan||lower bigrade}}, where the ''-gu'' ending only ever became ''-ge'', never ''-gi''.  That said, ancient Japanese did have verbs that were effectively {{l|en|ambitransitive}}, where transitivity was conveyed by context and by conjugation pattern.  The lower-bigrade conjugation of transitive classical verb {{m|ja|投ぐ|tr=nagu}} suggests the potential existence of an intransitive variant with the regular {{m|ja|四段活用|tr=yodan katsuyō||quadrigrade conjugation}}, where the final ''-gu'' would have become ''-gi''.

